# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-seed-oil
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-seed-oil/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:apple-seed-oil/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:apple-seed-oil/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:apple-seed-oil/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:apple-seed-oil/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:apple-seed-oil/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:apple-seed-oil/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:apple-seed-oil/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:apple-seed-oil/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:apple-seed-oil/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:apple-seed-oil/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:apple-seed-oil/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:apple-seed-oil/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:apple-seed-oil/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:apple-seed-oil/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:apple-seed-oil/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:apple-seed-oil/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:apple-seed-oil/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:apple-seed-oil/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] An **alkyd** is a polyester resin modified by the addition of fatty acids and other components.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Alkyds are derived from polyols and organic acids including dicarboxylic acids or carboxylic acid anhydride and triglyceride oils.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] The term *alkyd* is a modification of the original name "alcid", reflecting the fact that they are derived from *alc*ohol and organic ac*id*s.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] The inclusion of a fatty acid confers a tendency to form flexible coatings.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Alkyds are used in paints, varnishes and in moulds for casting.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] They are the dominant resin or binder in most commercial oil-based coatings.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Approximately 200,000 tons of alkyd resins are produced each year.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] The original alkyds were compounds of glycerol and phthalic acid sold under the name Glyptal.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] These were sold as substitutes for the darker-colored copal resins, thus creating alkyd varnishes that were much paler in colour.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] From these, the alkyds that are known today were developed.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Alkyd resins may be classified as drying (including semi drying) and nondrying.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Both types are typically produced from dicarboxylic acids or anhydrides, such as phthalic anhydride or maleic anhydride, and polyols, such as trimethylolpropane, glycerine, or pentaerythritol.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Alkyds are a synthetic resin and used in items such as paints.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] They are not the same as resin derived from natural sources such as plants.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] For the drying resins, triglycerides are derived from polyunsaturated fatty acids (often derived from plant and vegetable oils, e.g. linseed oil).
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] These drying alkyds are cured by the oxygen in air.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] The drying speed and the nature of the coatings depends on the amount and type of drying oil employed (more polyunsaturated oil means faster reaction in air) and presence of catalysts, the so-called oil drying agents.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] These catalysts are metal complexes that catalyze crosslinking of the unsaturated sites.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Cobalt salts are particularly effective and widely used.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Because of the alleged carcinogenicity of cobalt, some researchers are attempting to develop non-cobalt catalysts as replacements in alkyd coatings; none have been found yet that are as effective as cobalt.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Alkyd resins are produced in two processes: the fatty acid process and the alcoholysis or monoglyceride process.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Higher-quality, higher-performance alkyds are produced in the fatty acid process, in which the composition of the resulting resin may be more precisely controlled.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] In this process, an acid anhydride, a polyol and an unsaturated fatty acid are combined and cooked together until the product has achieved a predetermined level of viscosity.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Pentaerythritol based alkyds are made this way.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] More economical alkyd resins are produced from the alcoholysis or glyceride process, in which end-product quality control is not as paramount.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] In this process, raw vegetable oil, high in unsaturated component, is combined with additional polyol and heated to cause transesterification of the triglycerides into a mixture of mono- and diglyceride oils.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Acid anhydride is added to the resulting mixture to build the molecular weight of the resin into roughly the same product as with the fatty acid process.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] However, the alcoholysis process produces a more randomly oriented structure.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] To remove the water produced as a by-product and to increase the reaction rate, surplus phthalic anhydride is added.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Water is thus removed with the unreacted acid by heating the bulk to a specific temperature.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] The reaction is not as controllable as would be desired, so a new process was introduced in which xylene is added to produce an azeotrope with the water.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] This gives greater control at a lower temperature and also produces resins at a lower viscosity, useful in making high-solids paints.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] In both cases, the resulting product is a polyester resin to which pendant drying oil groups are attached.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] At the conclusion of each process the resin is purified, diluted in solvent and sold to paint and varnish makers.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Alkyd or oil-urethane binders are used in casting for the creation of sand-based moulds.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] The alkyd resin is mixed with a polymeric isocyanate and a metallic drier, which speeds up the reaction.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Unlike other no-bake mould technologies, the process yields no toxic fumes, but the moulds need more air-curing time.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Alkyd resins are usually classed as long oil, medium oil and short oil.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] These terms represent the oil length in the resin.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Alkyds are also modified with phenolic resin, styrene, vinyl toluene, acrylic monomers (to make them dry more quickly) and isocyanates to produce a polyurethane modified alkyd.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Urethane alkyds are manufactured by reacting the OH groups residual on the alkyd with NCO groups from an isocyanate often TDI.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] By adding certain modifying resins, it is possible to produce thixotropic alkyds for decorative use such as non-drip paints.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] The latest alkyds are short oil resins in which the oil length is shortened by use of a polymeric chain stopper usually a monobasic acid such as benzoic acid or *para*-*tert*-butylbenzoic acid (Alkydal M 48).
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] These have a better controlled molecular weight distribution and better durability.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Alkyds for decorative use have extra oil cooked in to lengthen them and to make them more durable.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Short oil resins used in stoving enamels are made from non-drying saturated oils or fatty acids.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] These usually have much higher hydroxyl and acid values to be able to react with the hydroxyl groups of the amino resins.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] These mixtures are usually stabilized with amines to prevent gelling on storage.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Non-drying/plasticizer resins are made from castor, palm, coconut oils and Cardura (the proprietary name of a synthetic ester of versatic acid).
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Dehydrated castor oil was at one time the only oil permitted in resin manufacture in India; no edible oils were allowed.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] They may be used to formulate flame-retardant coatings.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] As with many resin systems and coatings, alkyds may be hybridized with other resin technologies.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Although urethane alkyds are in effect a hybrid, novel technologies include manufacturing a moisture-curable polyurethane alkyd.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Grafting of silicon based materials onto alkyds has also been researched.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] As part of an effort to use more recycled materials, alkyds have been produced that are made from scrap PET bottles.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] There has been a general trend worldwide to formulate resins and coatings that are waterborne rather than formulated with solvent as waterbased materials are perceived to be environmentally friendly.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Waterborne alkyds have thus been made available too.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] One method is to acrylic-modify the alkyd to make it water-reducible.
[src:apple-seed-oil/alkyd-resin] Synthesis techniques of acrylic-modified water-reducible alkyds to improve corrosion performance have likewise been studied.
[src:apple-seed-oil/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:apple-seed-oil/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:apple-seed-oil/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:apple-seed-oil/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:apple-seed-oil/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:apple-seed-oil/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apple-seed-oil/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:apple-seed-oil/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:apple-seed-oil/apple-seed-oil] Apple seed oil may be used as an edible oil, with the oil cake being used to supplement animal feed.
[src:apple-seed-oil/apple-seed-oil] Apple seed oil has a relatively high iodine value and because of this it is used in the production of alkyd resins, shoe polish and varnish.
[src:apple-seed-oil/apple-seed-oil] Apple seed oils consist of predominantly unsaturated fatty acids, linoleic acid (50.7-51.4%), oleic acid (37.49-38.55%).
[src:apple-seed-oil/apple-seed-oil] Saturated fatty acids present in apple seed oil are palmitic acid (6.51-6.60%), stearic acid (1.75-1.96%) and arachidic acid (1.49-1.54%).
